From [MSDN](https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/standard/base-types/regular-expression-options#default-options)

> The `^` and `$` language elements match the beginning and end of the input string.

I am using pattern (in code below) to ensure that input is valid email. It matches inputs like `test@test.com` and rejects inputs that are not valid email. Interestingly, some times input contains a trailing new line character. I would expect the pattern to reject inputs like `test@test.com\n`. However, it seems that regex match `$` with `\n` and returns true. Validation succeeds in my system but the email address is rejected by other systems. This is expected as input with trailing new line is clearly not a valid email address.

**Why does `Regex.IsMatch()` returns `True` when it should not?**

### Sample program

```c#
    using System;
    using System.Text.RegularExpressions;
					
    public class Program
    {
        public static void Main()
        {
            var input = "test@test.com\n";
            var pattern = @"^([a-zA-Z0-9_\-\.]+)@([a-zA-Z0-9_\-\.]+)\.([a-zA-Z]{2,5}){1,25}$";
            
            var test1 = Regex.IsMatch(input, pattern, RegexOptions.ExplicitCapture);
            var test2 = Regex.IsMatch(input, pattern, RegexOptions.ExplicitCapture | RegexOptions.Singleline);
            var test3 = Regex.IsMatch(input, pattern, RegexOptions.ExplicitCapture | RegexOptions.Multiline);
            var test4 = Regex.IsMatch(input, pattern);
            
            Console.WriteLine(test1);
            Console.WriteLine(test2);
            Console.WriteLine(test3);
            Console.WriteLine(test4);
        }
    }
```

### Expected output
```
    False
    False
    True
    False
```
### Actual output
```
    True
    True
    True
    True
